// EXPECT: 99
// ADR-0071 Lát 2 §2.A: a BARE identifier in a match arm is ALWAYS a binding
// (catch-all), NEVER a variant match — even when spelled like a real variant.
// The arm `Green` is a binding; the scrutinee is `Color::Red` (a DIFFERENT
// variant), so the binding still captures it and returns 99 — proving `Green`
// did NOT match the `Green` variant by name. A hypothetical "match-on-name"
// resurrection would make `Green` match only the Green variant → `Color::Red`
// falls through → non-exhaustive E1026 → this fixture breaks. The Red-vs-Green
// mismatch is what makes the tooth bite a full resurrection, not just a no-op.
//
// LOAD-BEARING POISON = remove `Pattern::Variable` from the §2.A catch-all
// (exprs.rs:1807 exhaustiveness short-circuit + lib.rs enum default_bb): the
// bare arm stops being a catch-all → E1026 "missing Red, Green, Blue". NOTE the
// old typecheck guess-hack is NOT the poison here — its output has no consumer
// (the lower routes `Pattern::Variable`→catch-all off the AST node, never via a
// resolution), so re-adding it is inert and would NOT flip this fixture.
enum Color { Red, Green, Blue }

function classify(c: Color) -> Integer = match c {
    Green => 99,
}

function main() -> Integer = classify(Color::Red)
